<DOC><DOCNO> ZF310-633-239 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 633 239.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  April 22 1991 v8 n16 p24(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>News briefs.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Graphics Boards/CardsThree-Dimensional GraphicsDisk DrivesFloppy DiskTrackballsProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Matrox Boards BringandM;3-D Graphics to the PCandM;In an attempt to bring workstationlike 3-D graphics to the PC, MatroxElectronics Systems Ltd. recently announced the MG-3D and MG-3D Ultra, a pairof high-resolution graphics cards.andM;The MG-3D and MG-3D Ultra offer users such 3-D rendering features as shadingand rotation from inside AutoCAD release 11, said company officials inDorval, Quebec.andM;The MG-3D, an AT-bus version, touts a resolution of 1,024 by 768 pixels and12-bit color.andP;  The MG-3D Ultra, for the 32-bit Extended Industry StandardArchitecture bus, offers 1,280-by-1,024-pixel resolution and 24-bit color.andO;The MG-3D is priced at $3,495; the MG-3D Ultra at $5,995.andP;  Both boards areavailable immediately.andM;Matrox can be reached at (514) 685-2630.andM;--------------------Mitsubishi 2.88M-ByteandM;Floppy Aims at IBM EntryandM;Gearing up for IBM's expected June introduction of a 2.88M-byte 3-1/2-inchfloppy drive, Mitsubishi Electronics America Inc. earlier this monthannounced its own 2.88M-byte floppy drive.andM;The MF356C can be used with conventional 720K-, 1.44M- and new 2.88M-bytefloppy disks.andP;  The drives is priced in volume for OEMs at $70 per drive, saidcompany officials in Torrance, Calif.andM;Mitsubishi can be reached at (213) 515-3993.andM;--------------------Briefly Noted: Logitech Inc., of Fremont, Calif., earlier this monthannounced the TrackMan Portable, a thumb-operated, $169 trackball designedfor use with laptops.andP;  It will be available in July.andP;  Logitech can becontacted at (415) 795-8500.andO;</TEXT></DOC>